# Chrome DevTools MCP

Live DOM / focus / accessibility inspection via [`chrome-devtools-mcp`](https://github.com/ChromeDevTools/chrome-devtools-mcp), attached to the WSL-installed Google Chrome. Use when a UI bug (focus management, ARIA, etc.) can't be diagnosed from source alone.

Running Chrome inside WSL (instead of bridging to the Windows install) keeps the whole debugging flow on one side of the WSL↔Windows boundary — no port-forwarding or host-IP resolution. The WSL Chrome profile is isolated from any Windows browser and is signed into the test tenant only.

## One-time setup
- `google-chrome` installed in WSL (Ubuntu `.deb` from Google is fine).
- Register the MCP in Claude (user scope):
  ```bash
  claude mcp add chrome-devtools --scope user -- npx chrome-devtools-mcp@latest --browser-url http://127.0.0.1:9222
  ```

## Per-session
1. Launch Chrome (idempotent — no-op if the debug port is already answering):
   ```bash
   chrome-debug
   ```
   Script at `~/.local/bin/chrome-debug` runs `google-chrome --remote-debugging-port=9222 --user-data-dir=~/.cache/chrome-debug-profile`. WSLg surfaces the window in Windows automatically.
2. Sign into the test tenant if prompted — credentials live in Bitwarden.
3. Navigate to the page that exhibits the bug being diagnosed.
4. Tell Claude "Chrome is ready" — Claude connects via the MCP at `http://127.0.0.1:9222`.

## Safety
- **Test tenant only.** Never sign into the WSL Chrome with your real work account.
- Close Chrome when the debugging session ends so the debugging port isn't left open.
- Every MCP tool call prompts for approval — review anything that looks like it's executing JS against sensitive state.
- Browser state stays in `~/.cache/chrome-debug-profile`, isolated from any other browser profile.

## Iframe debugging
- `press_key` via CDP doesn't reliably deliver Tab (and likely other keys) into focused iframe content. For keyboard-behavior tests, dispatch a synthetic `KeyboardEvent` via `evaluate_script`, or have the user drive the keyboard directly.
- Cross-origin iframes (e.g. Teams hosting Neptune): parent-document access to `iframe.contentDocument` is blocked. Use element UIDs from `take_snapshot` instead — they work across frame boundaries when passed as `args` to `evaluate_script`, and `document.activeElement` inside the function resolves to the element's own frame.

# Cockpit — ADO Task Management Workflow

## Session Startup
1. Read ~/cockpit/state/ado-tasks.md for current task state
2. If the file is empty or the Sprint ID is stale (sprint dates have passed), run `/standup` automatically
3. If state exists, summarize: items tracked, in-progress/done/blocked counts

## Available Commands
- `/standup` — Fetch current sprint, reconcile state, report priorities
- `/daily` — Daily review: unified dashboard of ADO items + Logseq TODOs, with triage recommendations
- `/work [ID...]` — Assess fitness, plan, and launch agents for work items
- `/status` — Check in-flight agents, update state, report progress
- `/browser-queue` — List and manage pending browser tasks

